column9:
865864: Before diving into today's example, we'll go through some of the concepts of todays lecture.

What is the main reason RCTs are considered the best way to estimate causal effects?
column11: 865865: In an RCT, what does random assignment help to ensure?
column13: 865866: What is the purpose of including variables, other than the treatment variable, (sometimes referred to as covariates or control variables) in a regression model?
column15: 865867: Open the script for the quiz. You have to fill in the relevant code where it says "*******"
column17:
865868: If you read the articles, you will know that the partners behind the research were really interested in gender bias in educational choices. Hence, if and why males and females tend to pick different educations in Denmark.
Nurse ("sygeplejerske") is often used as a education that has a gender bias problem in their student composition. Lets use both the survey and Statistics Denmark's API to examine that!In the survey data, the variable "RealEducationPreference" indicates which education the respondent expect to apply for. Use the variable to examine how big a proportion of the total number of respondents in the survey, state that they would like to study "Sygeplejerske" (=Nurse)?
column19: 865869: Now, use the Statistics Denmark API to find out how many students that were enrolled as "Sygepleje og sundhedspleje" (=Nurse) as of 1st of October 2022. Select the correct answer below based on the "value" column.
column21: 865872: In the last part of the quiz, we will get back to the question of gender bias. Use the RealEducationPreference variable to examine which education in the survey data that has the highest procentage of men compared to women. Select the answer below.
column23: 865873: Use the Statistics Denmark API to look up what the proportion of men and women is among their students on the education "Elektriker" as of 1st of October 2022. What is the share of men in the register?
column25:
865874: Back to the experiment. Examine how information on gender distribution of students enrolled on the education (ExpGenderDistribution) impact the rating of the education (ExpEducationRating) by potential students. Answer the questions below.
1) Summarise data on ExpGenderDistribution and calculate the mean ofExpEducationRatingwithin each treatment group. What is the mean rating of a education if the respondent was shown the gender distribution treatment "19% women and 81% men"? Answer: [MeanEduRating]
2) Now estimate the effect of gender distribution (ExpGenderDistribution) on rating of the education (ExpEducationRating). What is the effect of a education where "79% women and 21% men" are enrolled compared to "19% women and 81% men" (reference group) on respondent's rating of the education? Answer: [estimate]
3) Is any of the treatment groups significantly different in their rating compared to the reference group ("19% women and 81% men") at a conventional 5% significance level? Answer: [sig]
column27: 865879: On a scale from 0 (the worst possible quiz for this lecture) to 10 (the best possible quiz for this lecture), how would you rate the quiz, that you have just completed?
column29:

If you don't have any suggestions, just type a blank space
column31:
865870: Okay - lets turn to the experimental design of the survey. In the first part of the quiz, we will examine how information on the unemployment percentage (ExpUnemploymentPct) impact the rating of the education (ExpEducationRating).
Firstly, we need to check whether the unemployment treatment (ExpUnemploymentPct) is randomly distributed. Answer the following questions:
1) Summarise data on ExpUnemploymentPct to get the count and proportion of each treatment group. Is the treatment groups more or less evenly distributed? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["Yes", "No"]

.
2) Is the unemployment treatment balanced across Gender? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["Yes", "No"]


3) Is the unemployment treatment balanced across AgeCategory? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["Yes", "No"]


Secondly, we will have a look at the effect of unemployment percentage (ExpUnemploymentPct) on rating of the education (ExpEducationRating). Answer the following questions:
1) Summarise data on ExpUnemploymentPct and calculate the mean of ExpEducationRatingwithin each treatment group. What is the mean rating of a education if the respondent was shown the unemployment treatment "1.2% unemployed"? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["5.12", "5.09", "4.97", "4.93", "4.85"]


2) Now estimate the effect of unemployment percentage (ExpUnemploymentPct) on rating of the education (ExpEducationRating). What is the effect of a education having an unemployment percentage at "18.9% unemployed" compared "1.2% unemployed" (reference group) on respondent's rating of the education? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["5.12", "-0.032", "-0.151", "-0.191", "-0.276"]


3) Is the difference between the treatment groups systematic or likely the result of happenstance? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["The difference is systematic because the coefficient is statistically significant", "The result is systematic because the treatment was randomized", "The effect is too small to be systematic", "The effect is statistically insignificant"]
column33:
865878: Gender distributionof students enrolled on the educationdoes notseem to have an effect on the rating of the education. But what if the effect is averaged out by men going in one direction and women going in another? Lets examine that hypothesis by answering the following questions:
1) Group byExpGenderDistributionandGenderto calculate the mean rating of educations within each experimental condition and gender. At what level ofExpGenderDistributionis the difference between "Mand" and "Kvinde" largest? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["19% women and 81% men", "34% women and 66% men", "51% women and 49% men", "65% women and 35% men", "79% women and 21% men"]


2) Subset the data set to only include "Kvinde" on the Gendervariable. On this new data set, estimate the effect ofExpGenderDistributiononExpEducationRating. What is the estimate of a education where "65% women and 35% men" are enrolled compared to "19% women and 81% men" (reference group) on respondent's rating of the education? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["0.015", "0.096", "0.231", "0.043"]

 
3) Is the effect of "65% women and 35% men" compared to the reference group ("19% women and 81% men") statistically significant at a 5% significance level? Answer: 
  
    [ Select ]
  
  ["Yes", "No"]
